reviewText: Two strangers, Claire "Mickey" Tremane  (Margot Kidder- BLACK CHRISTMAS, THE AMITYVILLE HORROR) and Daniel Hawkins (Michael Sarrazin) witness a murder, and recover the victim's suitcase full of money.  Naturally, the criminals want the money, so our heroes are in big trouble! Meanwhile, the police get involved, but seem to be hiding something. Now, Claire and Daniel must work together to figure out what's going on, before they both wind up dead. KEEPING TRACK is a pretty light-weight thriller, but it's enjoyable enough to remain watchable to the end. Besides, Margot Kidder fans will be glad to see her in almost every scene!...  P.S.- The one big drawback is the hideous, mind-mulching "pan flute" soundtrack! Yecch!...
summary: "Well, There You Have It Ladies And Gentleman! A Carload of Satisfied Canadians!"...

reviewText: This 1977 Canadian film is a fast-paced but rather frenetic espionage drama.  Margot Kidder, playing a bank executive, and the late Michael Sarrazin, playing a journalist, take an ill-fated train ride, and discover an international conspiracy involving a new computer chip.  The plot is actually quite good.  There are enough twists to keep the viewer guessing, and an intriguing reversal at the end.  The problem in this film is that it alternates between trying to be a serious thriller and a lighthearted adventure, ending up being more of the latter.  The comedic elements end up detracting from the real tension in the plot.

reviewText: This is a low key film with an interesting plot line that caters to my partiality for stories about unlikely people, who would rarely get along in real life, having to join forces to resolve an issue-such as surviving until the next day. Nice, understated and believable performances.  I watched this film to the end, which is rare for me these days, as my boredom with movies/television threshold has accountably dropped to infinitesimal.  I usually leave a video within twenty minutes preferring to listen to a recorded book.
